RUSH HOUR: The stories you need to know today Live Updates Image Turnbull says that Trump has a commitment to the the refugee deal 0:30 
On 60 Minutes with Laurie Oakes, Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull says that Donald Trump has committed to the refugee deal, but will not have to honour it. February 5th 2017 10 hours ago /video/video.news.com.au/News/Politics/ Saturday Night Live has spoofed Donald Trump once again. But this time, our Prime Minister has been thrown into the mix too. 
Man arrested six months after jogger slaying 
Police have made a long-awaited arrest over the killing of Queens jogger Karina Vetrano. 
Twenty-year-old Chanel Lewis, from east New York, will be charged with murder and sexual assault, based on DNA testing and “detailed incriminating statements and admissions” he made to detectives. 
Chief of Detectives Robert Boyce said Lewis, who has no prior arrest record, was taken into custody on Saturday night. 
Lewis was interviewed by police on Thursday after being identified as a potential suspect. He voluntarily provided a DNA sample, which was then matched with DNA recovered from under Ms Vetrano’s fingernails, her back and mobile phone, Boyce said. 
Sources told The New York Post the man is in his 20s and had been on the police radar for a while, after an off-duty officer saw him acting suspiciously. He had been questioned previously, and last week had agreed to a DNA sample. 
A close friend of Ms Vetrano’s told the New York Daily News : “I’m literally shaking right now,” upon hearing the news. Police have made a long-awaited arrest over the killing of Queens jogger Karina Vetrano. Source: Supplied 
7.30am 
Duterte threatens air strikes against rebels 
Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte has issued a warning that the military is ready to respond with air strikes and new offensives if communist rebels launch new attacks. 
Mr Duterte called the rebels “terrorists,” as months of steady progress in talks brokered by Norway rapidly turned hostile after New People’s Army rebels killed six soldiers and kidnapped two others in fresh violence. 
“It seems to me that these terrorists want another 50 years of war, of killing of Filipinos,” he said. 
“I don’t want a bloody thing, but if they choose to do it, fine. 
“With my lifting of the ceasefire, they can begin their attacks and we are prepared and I will use the assets. We have so many planes now, we have jets, I will drop all (the bombs).” Rodrigo Duterte has threatened air strikes against communist rebels. Source: AFP 
7.15am 
Trump’s shocking Putin admission 
Jaws have dropped within the Republican Party over the following exchange between President Donald Trump and Fox News anchor Bill O’Reilly. Preview: Trump talks @oreillyfactor tmrw before #SuperBowl on @FOXTV - on Putin's record, "what do you think? Our country's so innocent?" pic.twitter.com/ohQ8VknFDS — Chris Snyder (@ChrisSnyderFox) February 4, 2017 
Several of Mr Trump’s fellow Republicans have condemned his remarks, saying there is no moral equivalence between the United States and a regime known for killing its political opponents. 
The full interview will air at 8AM (AEST) today on Fox News. 
7.00am 
Australian woman killed in Thailand 
An Australian woman has been killed in a jet-ski collision with her partner in waters off the Thai tourist island of Phuket. 
Emily Jayne Collie, 20, suffered severe neck and shoulder injuries in the crash near Kata Beach late on Sunday afternoon, Thai media reports. 
Ms Collie, reportedly from Kyabram, and her partner, named by The Sun as Tommy, had reportedly both hired jet-skis. 
The paper reported that the couple smashed into each other after they were both blinded by strong sun light reflected from the sea on the island’s Kata Beach at 4.45pm local time. 
Ms Collie was reportedly unconscious when she was pulled out of the sea by lifeguards. 
Alongside her partner, they frantically tried to perform CPR but Ms Collie was pronounced dead before arriving at hospital, Bangkok Post reported. Her partner suffered minor injuries. 
News Corp Australia has contacted the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade for comment. Emily Jayne Collier with her partner Tommy. Source: Supplied 
6.30am 
Wild weather to ease in Victoria 
Thunderstorms and flooding are expected to ease across Victoria this afternoon, after a wild and woolly end to the weekend that led to hundreds of emergency call outs. 
The Bureau of Meteorology said weather conditions would ease today, with a high of only 19C and rains clearing. 
5-10mm of rain is expected, following a wet Sunday that saw up to 33mm in some parts of Melbourne and up to 46mm at Arthurs Seat. 
State Emergency Service crews have responded to 328 calls for assistance since 10pm last night with coastal areas such as Sorrento the hardest hit. 
A plane was also diverted due to Melbourne’s weather conditions, leaving passengers stranded in Adelaide. 
6.15am 
Support for Pauline Hanson surges in polls 
Malcolm Turnbull has copped a belting in the polls, with support for the Coalition collapsing to the lowest level since Tony Abbott was toppled as Prime Minister. 
The first Newspoll of the year, taken for The Australian , shows the government trailing Labor by 46 to 54 per cent in two-party terms, with support for independents surging from 15 to 19 per cent. 
Following Mr Turnbull’s explosive phone call with US President Donald Trump over the refugee deal, the Coalition’s primary vote has tumbled four points over the summer holidays to 35 per cent. 
Meanwhile, Pauline Hanson’s One Nation has a national primary vote of eight per cent. This is the same level of support it achieved at the 1998 federal election. 
It comes as Senator Hanson outlined her blueprint for Australia, which would include forcing newlyweds to have pre-nuptial agreements and changes to the tax system. 
The One Nation leader said she’d also cut the number of politicians, limit migration, introduce an Australian identity card, and axe the GST and consider a flat two per cent tax rate if she ran the country. Malcolm Turnbull has copped a belting in the polls, with support for the Coalition collapsing to the lowest level since Tony Abbott was toppled as Prime Minister. Source: News Corp Australia
